anging norms and new technologies affect older people’s relationship careers, their attitudes to repartnering and in the formation of new relationships? Which forms do these new unions take? What does a new intimate relationship offer older men and women and what are the consequences for social integration? What is the role and meaning of sex? By introducing a gains-perspective the book challenges stereotypes of old age as a period of loss and decline. It also challenges the image of older people as conservative, and instead presents them as an avant-garde that often experiment with new ways of being together.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aAgingxSocial aspects. 0aIntimacy (Psychology). 0aLove. 0aOlder peoplexSexual behavior. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aCalasanti, Toni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhillipson, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScharf, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aÖberg, Peter, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311119663340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447326519423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447326519/original  a978-3-11-119663-3  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles